      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The two articles about energy policy (Business Forum, March 27) overlooked the fundamental element of why energy policy is needed: consumption. Discussing paths to sound energy policy without considering energy efficiency research and development overlooks a critical avenue to a sustainable energy future.</p>
        <p>Even without energy prices reflecting their true marginal costs (for example, $47 billion to ''protect'' the Persian Gulf, acid rain, environmental degradation) many investments in energy efficiency prove that it is cheaper and wiser to use saved energy for new energy demand rather than developing new sources.</p>
        <p>What is needed is a policy that recognizes there is room for vast, cost-effective improvements in energy efficiency in industrial, commercial and residential consumption. Also, it must be understood that if it is more economical to spend money to save energy than it is to develop new sources, our energy policy should reflect this and foster the necessary technologies.  WILLIAM TROPER</p>
        <p>Montague, Mass., March 31</p>
      </block>
